The '''Eglisau–Neuhausen railway line''' is a cross-border railway line in Europe. 

==Description==
The line links [[Eglisau]] in the Swiss [[canton of Zurich]] with the [[Schaffhausen|city of Schaffhausen]] in the Swiss [[canton of Schaffhausen]], crossing some {{convert|8|km}} of the German state of [[Baden-Württemberg]] in between. It thus crosses the [[Germany–Switzerland border]] twice.<ref name=edsp110>{{cite book | title = Eisenbahnatlas Deutschland | year = 2009 | publisher = Verlag Schweers + Wall GmbH | isbn=978-3-89494-139-0 | pages = 110–111}}</ref>

The line is {{convert|17.88|km}} long, standard gauge and electrified at {{15 kV AC}} supplied by [[overhead line]]. The section between Hüntwangen-Wil and Rafz is double track, whilst the rest of the line is single track.<ref name=edsp110/>

Schaffhausen was first connected to the Swiss railway system in 1857 with the opening of the [[Rheinfall Railway]]. Whilst this line was entirely on Swiss soil, and provided a direct link to the [[Winterthur|city of Winterthur]], it only provided a rather indirect route to the rest of Switzerland and the [[Gotthard Railway]]. The [[Swiss Northeastern Railway]] therefore constructed the Eglisau to Neuhausen line, which opened in 1897.

The construction of the line involved the building of several civil engineering structures, including the {{convert|439|m}} [[Eglisau railway bridge]] across the [[Rhine]] at the southern end of the line. At the northern end of the line, two tunnels were necessary, with lengths of {{convert|112|m}} and {{convert|144|m}}.

The whole line, including the section in Germany, now belongs to the [[Swiss Federal Railways]], and is subject to Swiss rail regulations and Swiss domestic rail fares.<ref name=edsp110/> Besides the junction stations of [[Eglisau railway station|Eglisau]] and [[Neuhausen railway station|Neuhausen]], there are five intermediate stations, of which three are in Switzerland and two in Germany. A sixth intermediate station, at Altenburg-Rheinau, was closed in 2011, whilst the [[Neuhausen Rheinfall railway station|Neuhausen Rheinfall]] station was opened in 2015.

The line carries an hourly service of long-distance passenger trains between [[Zurich]] and Schaffhausen, with some trains operating as far as [[Frankfurt]] and [[Bern]]. Trains on the [[Zurich S-Bahn]] line [[S9 (ZVV)|S9]] operate half-hourly from Zurich as far as [[Rafz]] (just before the German border), with alternate trains continuing to Schaffhausen. Schaffhausen S-Bahn line S22 provides a local service from [[Jestetten]] to Schaffhausen.<ref name=zvv-ln>{{cite web | url=https://www.zvv.ch/content/dam/zvv/fahrplan/pdf/sbahn_A3_2017_rgb.pdf |title=S-Bahn trains, buses and boats |publisher=ZVV |accessdate=18 September 2018 | deadurl=no |archivedate=18 September 2018 | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180918165540/https://www.zvv.ch/content/dam/zvv/fahrplan/pdf/sbahn_A3_2017_rgb.pdf}}</ref><ref name=tt-760>{{cite web |url=http://www.fahrplanfelder.ch/fileadmin/fap_pdf_fields/2018/760.pdf |title=Schaffhausen–Bülach–Zürich |publisher=Bundesamt für Verkehr |accessdate=18 September 2018 |deadurl=no | archivedate=18 September 2018 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180918164757/http://www.fahrplanfelder.ch/fileadmin/fap_pdf_fields/2018/760.pdf}}</ref> Freight trains also use the line between Germany and the Gotthard route.

==Accidents and incidents==
On 20 February 2015, [[Rafz train crash|a collision occurred]] between an [[Interregio]] train and an [[S-Bahn]] train at {{rws|Rafz}}.

